05008nam a22008295i 9780823290239DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20212021nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780823290239  a(DE-B1597)577741  a(OCoLC)1231605823  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aART0590002bisacsh1 aKaraca, Banu, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe National Frame :bArt and State Violence in Turkey and Germany /cBanu Karaca. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (288 p.) :b22 b/w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Intimate Encounters -- t1 Modernity, Nationalism, and Civilizing the Arts -- t2 Art Worlds: Of Friends, Foes, and Working for the Greater Good -- t3 Governing Culture, Producing Modern Citizens -- t4 The Art of Forgetting -- t5 The Politics of Art and Censorship -- t6 Enterprising Art, Aestheticizing Business -- tInstead of a Conclusion: Meeting, Again -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBased on long-term ethnographic research in the art worlds of Istanbul and Berlin, The National Frame rethinks the politics of art by focusing on the role of art in state governance. It argues that artistic practices, arts patronage and sponsorship, collecting and curating art, and the modalities of censorship continue to be refracted through the conceptual lens of the nation-state, despite the globalization of the arts. By examining discussions of the civilizing function of art in Turkey and Germany and particularly moments in which art is seen to cede this function, The National Frame reveals the histories of violence on which the production, circulation, and, very understanding of art are predicated. Karaca examines this darker side of art in two cities in which art and its institutions have been intertwined with symbolic and material dispossession. The particularities of German and Turkish contexts, both marked by attempts to claim modern nationhood through the arts; illuminate how art is staked to memory and erasure, resistance and restoration; and why art has been at once vital and unwieldy for national projects. As art continues to be called upon to engage the past and imagine different futures, The National Frame explores how to reclaim art’s emancipatory potential.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 4aAnthropology. 4aArt & Visual Culture. 4aMiddle Eastern Studies. 7aART / Museum Studies.2bisacsh  aEast/West binary.  aanthropology of art.  aart world.  acomparison.  acultural memory.  acultural policy.  adispossession.  amodernity.  anationalism.  astate violence.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts 2021z9783110753790oZDB-23-DPK08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts, Architecture and Design 2021 Englishz978311075403208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073909140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082329023940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823290239423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823290239/original  a978-3-11-073909-1  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-075400-1  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishb2021  a978-3-11-075403-2  EBOOK PACKAGE Arts, Architecture and Design 2021 Englishb2021  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBKALL  